</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">As use of digital breast tomosynthesis becomes increasingly widespread, new management challenges are inevitable because tomosynthesis may reveal suspicious lesions not visible at conventional two-dimensional (2D) full-field digital mammography. Architectural distortion is a mammographic finding associated with a high positive predictive value for malignancy. It is detected more frequently at tomosynthesis than at 2D digital mammography and may even be occult at conventional 2D imaging. Few studies have focused on tomosynthesis-detected architectural distortions to date, and optimal management of these distortions has yet to be well defined. Since implementing tomosynthesis at our institution in 2011, we have learned some practical ways to assess architectural distortion. Because distortions may be subtle, tomosynthesis localization tools plus improved visualization of adjacent landmarks are crucial elements in guiding mammographic identification of elusive distortions. These same tools can guide more focused ultrasonography (US) of the breast, which facilitates detection and permits US-guided tissue sampling. Some distortions may be sonographically occult, in which case magnetic resonance imaging may be a reasonable option, both to increase diagnostic confidence and to provide a means for image-guided biopsy. As an alternative, tomosynthesis-guided biopsy, conventional stereotactic biopsy (when possible), or tomosynthesis-guided needle localization may be used to achieve tissue diagnosis. Practical uses for tomosynthesis in evaluation of architectural distortion are highlighted, potential complications are identified, and a working algorithm for management of tomosynthesis-detected architectural distortion is proposed.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2016</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150093">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150093">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig1a.jpeg" height="725" width="864" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Invasive ductal carcinoma manifesting as architectural distortion in dense breast tissue. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique (<abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr>) tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows an architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) less clearly depicts the architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Correlative ultrasonographic (US) image shows a hypoechoic mass with an indistinct hyperechoic halo. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph of specimen from US-guided core needle biopsy shows invasive ductal carcinoma (grade 2) and intraepithelial neoplasia (in situ carcinoma) with tubulolobular features. A permeative growth pattern into adipose tissue and fibrous septa is seen. The mass was staged pT1bN0 and was found to be estrogen receptor (<abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr>) positive, progesterone receptor (<abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr>) positive, and human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (<abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr>) negative. (Hemotoxylin-eosin [<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr>] stain; original magnification, ×1.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig1b.jpeg" height="725" width="811" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Invasive ductal carcinoma manifesting as architectural distortion in dense breast tissue. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique (<abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr>) tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows an architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) less clearly depicts the architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Correlative ultrasonographic (US) image shows a hypoechoic mass with an indistinct hyperechoic halo. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph of specimen from US-guided core needle biopsy shows invasive ductal carcinoma (grade 2) and intraepithelial neoplasia (in situ carcinoma) with tubulolobular features. A permeative growth pattern into adipose tissue and fibrous septa is seen. The mass was staged pT1bN0 and was found to be estrogen receptor (<abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr>) positive, progesterone receptor (<abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr>) positive, and human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (<abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr>) negative. (Hemotoxylin-eosin [<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr>] stain; original magnification, ×1.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig1c.jpeg" height="702" width="914" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Invasive ductal carcinoma manifesting as architectural distortion in dense breast tissue. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique (<abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr>) tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows an architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) less clearly depicts the architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Correlative ultrasonographic (US) image shows a hypoechoic mass with an indistinct hyperechoic halo. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph of specimen from US-guided core needle biopsy shows invasive ductal carcinoma (grade 2) and intraepithelial neoplasia (in situ carcinoma) with tubulolobular features. A permeative growth pattern into adipose tissue and fibrous septa is seen. The mass was staged pT1bN0 and was found to be estrogen receptor (<abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr>) positive, progesterone receptor (<abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr>) positive, and human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (<abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr>) negative. (Hemotoxylin-eosin [<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr>] stain; original magnification, ×1.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig1d.jpeg" height="702" width="761" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. Invasive ductal carcinoma manifesting as architectural distortion in dense breast tissue. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique (<abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr>) tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows an architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) less clearly depicts the architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Correlative ultrasonographic (US) image shows a hypoechoic mass with an indistinct hyperechoic halo. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph of specimen from US-guided core needle biopsy shows invasive ductal carcinoma (grade 2) and intraepithelial neoplasia (in situ carcinoma) with tubulolobular features. A permeative growth pattern into adipose tissue and fibrous septa is seen. The mass was staged pT1bN0 and was found to be estrogen receptor (<abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr>) positive, progesterone receptor (<abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr>) positive, and human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (<abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr>) negative. (Hemotoxylin-eosin [<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr>] stain; original magnification, ×1.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig2a.jpeg" height="639" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Complex sclerosing lesion manifesting as architectural distortion. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis spot compression image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows an architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced magnetic resonance (MR) subtraction image shows a correlative irregular enhancing mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Low-power photomicrograph of specimen from MR imaging–guided core needle biopsy shows radially arranged ducts around a central scar with entrapped ducts. Epithelial proliferation without atypia is evident in some of the ducts, which qualifies the finding as a complex sclerosing lesion. Histopathologic analysis after surgical excision showed a complex sclerosing papillary lesion with low-risk ductal intraepithelial neoplasia. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×1.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig2b.jpeg" height="712" width="606" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Complex sclerosing lesion manifesting as architectural distortion. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis spot compression image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows an architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced magnetic resonance (MR) subtraction image shows a correlative irregular enhancing mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Low-power photomicrograph of specimen from MR imaging–guided core needle biopsy shows radially arranged ducts around a central scar with entrapped ducts. Epithelial proliferation without atypia is evident in some of the ducts, which qualifies the finding as a complex sclerosing lesion. Histopathologic analysis after surgical excision showed a complex sclerosing papillary lesion with low-risk ductal intraepithelial neoplasia. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×1.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig2c.jpeg" height="710" width="719" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Complex sclerosing lesion manifesting as architectural distortion. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis spot compression image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows an architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced magnetic resonance (MR) subtraction image shows a correlative irregular enhancing mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Low-power photomicrograph of specimen from MR imaging–guided core needle biopsy shows radially arranged ducts around a central scar with entrapped ducts. Epithelial proliferation without atypia is evident in some of the ducts, which qualifies the finding as a complex sclerosing lesion. Histopathologic analysis after surgical excision showed a complex sclerosing papillary lesion with low-risk ductal intraepithelial neoplasia. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×1.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig3a.jpeg" height="689" width="903" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Tomosynthesis used to improve localization and guide targeted US of two areas of architectural distortion, one at a posterior depth and one located more anteriorly. <b>(a–c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows an anterior distortion (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) that is depicted more clearly on an <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(b)</b>. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(c)</b> shows a subtle posterior-depth distortion and mass (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>), findings seen at tomosynthesis only; the <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> image in <b>a</b> shows only a posterior asymmetry. Insets show zoomed-in area of interest. <b>(d, e)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis images show use of the localization bar. Because correlates for the two architectural distortions were not readily identified on a craniocaudal view, the tomosynthesis localization bar on <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> images was used to better pinpoint positions in the medial-to-lateral plane on the craniocaudal view. According to the localization bar, the anterior finding (arrows in <b>d</b>) is shown to be in the lateral breast, and the posterior finding (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) is shown to be in the medial breast. Tomosynthesis localization also guided US evaluation. <b>(f)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the anterior finding (which was seen mammographically in the upper outer quadrant) at the 2-o’clock position. <b>(g)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the posterior finding (seen mammographically in the upper inner quadrant) at the 11-o’clock position. <b>(h, i)</b> Craniocaudal <b>(h)</b> and mediolateral <b>(i)</b> postbiopsy <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images show the biopsy clips at 2 o’clock and 11 o’clock (arrows). Biopsy proved invasive lobular carcinoma (grade 2, stage pT3N1, <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive, <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive, <abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr> negative).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig3b.jpeg" height="689" width="772" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Tomosynthesis used to improve localization and guide targeted US of two areas of architectural distortion, one at a posterior depth and one located more anteriorly. <b>(a–c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows an anterior distortion (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) that is depicted more clearly on an <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(b)</b>. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(c)</b> shows a subtle posterior-depth distortion and mass (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>), findings seen at tomosynthesis only; the <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> image in <b>a</b> shows only a posterior asymmetry. Insets show zoomed-in area of interest. <b>(d, e)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis images show use of the localization bar. Because correlates for the two architectural distortions were not readily identified on a craniocaudal view, the tomosynthesis localization bar on <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> images was used to better pinpoint positions in the medial-to-lateral plane on the craniocaudal view. According to the localization bar, the anterior finding (arrows in <b>d</b>) is shown to be in the lateral breast, and the posterior finding (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) is shown to be in the medial breast. Tomosynthesis localization also guided US evaluation. <b>(f)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the anterior finding (which was seen mammographically in the upper outer quadrant) at the 2-o’clock position. <b>(g)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the posterior finding (seen mammographically in the upper inner quadrant) at the 11-o’clock position. <b>(h, i)</b> Craniocaudal <b>(h)</b> and mediolateral <b>(i)</b> postbiopsy <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images show the biopsy clips at 2 o’clock and 11 o’clock (arrows). Biopsy proved invasive lobular carcinoma (grade 2, stage pT3N1, <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive, <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive, <abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr> negative).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig3c.jpeg" height="859" width="619" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Tomosynthesis used to improve localization and guide targeted US of two areas of architectural distortion, one at a posterior depth and one located more anteriorly. <b>(a–c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows an anterior distortion (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) that is depicted more clearly on an <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(b)</b>. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(c)</b> shows a subtle posterior-depth distortion and mass (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>), findings seen at tomosynthesis only; the <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> image in <b>a</b> shows only a posterior asymmetry. Insets show zoomed-in area of interest. <b>(d, e)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis images show use of the localization bar. Because correlates for the two architectural distortions were not readily identified on a craniocaudal view, the tomosynthesis localization bar on <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> images was used to better pinpoint positions in the medial-to-lateral plane on the craniocaudal view. According to the localization bar, the anterior finding (arrows in <b>d</b>) is shown to be in the lateral breast, and the posterior finding (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) is shown to be in the medial breast. Tomosynthesis localization also guided US evaluation. <b>(f)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the anterior finding (which was seen mammographically in the upper outer quadrant) at the 2-o’clock position. <b>(g)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the posterior finding (seen mammographically in the upper inner quadrant) at the 11-o’clock position. <b>(h, i)</b> Craniocaudal <b>(h)</b> and mediolateral <b>(i)</b> postbiopsy <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images show the biopsy clips at 2 o’clock and 11 o’clock (arrows). Biopsy proved invasive lobular carcinoma (grade 2, stage pT3N1, <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive, <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive, <abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr> negative).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig3d.jpeg" height="859" width="616" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. Tomosynthesis used to improve localization and guide targeted US of two areas of architectural distortion, one at a posterior depth and one located more anteriorly. <b>(a–c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows an anterior distortion (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) that is depicted more clearly on an <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(b)</b>. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(c)</b> shows a subtle posterior-depth distortion and mass (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>), findings seen at tomosynthesis only; the <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> image in <b>a</b> shows only a posterior asymmetry. Insets show zoomed-in area of interest. <b>(d, e)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis images show use of the localization bar. Because correlates for the two architectural distortions were not readily identified on a craniocaudal view, the tomosynthesis localization bar on <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> images was used to better pinpoint positions in the medial-to-lateral plane on the craniocaudal view. According to the localization bar, the anterior finding (arrows in <b>d</b>) is shown to be in the lateral breast, and the posterior finding (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) is shown to be in the medial breast. Tomosynthesis localization also guided US evaluation. <b>(f)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the anterior finding (which was seen mammographically in the upper outer quadrant) at the 2-o’clock position. <b>(g)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the posterior finding (seen mammographically in the upper inner quadrant) at the 11-o’clock position. <b>(h, i)</b> Craniocaudal <b>(h)</b> and mediolateral <b>(i)</b> postbiopsy <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images show the biopsy clips at 2 o’clock and 11 o’clock (arrows). Biopsy proved invasive lobular carcinoma (grade 2, stage pT3N1, <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive, <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive, <abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr> negative).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig3e.jpeg" height="859" width="615" aria-labelledby="fig3e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3e</span>. Tomosynthesis used to improve localization and guide targeted US of two areas of architectural distortion, one at a posterior depth and one located more anteriorly. <b>(a–c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows an anterior distortion (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) that is depicted more clearly on an <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(b)</b>. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(c)</b> shows a subtle posterior-depth distortion and mass (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>), findings seen at tomosynthesis only; the <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> image in <b>a</b> shows only a posterior asymmetry. Insets show zoomed-in area of interest. <b>(d, e)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis images show use of the localization bar. Because correlates for the two architectural distortions were not readily identified on a craniocaudal view, the tomosynthesis localization bar on <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> images was used to better pinpoint positions in the medial-to-lateral plane on the craniocaudal view. According to the localization bar, the anterior finding (arrows in <b>d</b>) is shown to be in the lateral breast, and the posterior finding (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) is shown to be in the medial breast. Tomosynthesis localization also guided US evaluation. <b>(f)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the anterior finding (which was seen mammographically in the upper outer quadrant) at the 2-o’clock position. <b>(g)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the posterior finding (seen mammographically in the upper inner quadrant) at the 11-o’clock position. <b>(h, i)</b> Craniocaudal <b>(h)</b> and mediolateral <b>(i)</b> postbiopsy <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images show the biopsy clips at 2 o’clock and 11 o’clock (arrows). Biopsy proved invasive lobular carcinoma (grade 2, stage pT3N1, <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive, <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive, <abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr> negative).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig3e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig3f.jpeg" height="402" width="716" aria-labelledby="fig3f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3f</span>. Tomosynthesis used to improve localization and guide targeted US of two areas of architectural distortion, one at a posterior depth and one located more anteriorly. <b>(a–c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows an anterior distortion (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) that is depicted more clearly on an <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(b)</b>. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(c)</b> shows a subtle posterior-depth distortion and mass (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>), findings seen at tomosynthesis only; the <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> image in <b>a</b> shows only a posterior asymmetry. Insets show zoomed-in area of interest. <b>(d, e)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis images show use of the localization bar. Because correlates for the two architectural distortions were not readily identified on a craniocaudal view, the tomosynthesis localization bar on <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> images was used to better pinpoint positions in the medial-to-lateral plane on the craniocaudal view. According to the localization bar, the anterior finding (arrows in <b>d</b>) is shown to be in the lateral breast, and the posterior finding (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) is shown to be in the medial breast. Tomosynthesis localization also guided US evaluation. <b>(f)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the anterior finding (which was seen mammographically in the upper outer quadrant) at the 2-o’clock position. <b>(g)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the posterior finding (seen mammographically in the upper inner quadrant) at the 11-o’clock position. <b>(h, i)</b> Craniocaudal <b>(h)</b> and mediolateral <b>(i)</b> postbiopsy <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images show the biopsy clips at 2 o’clock and 11 o’clock (arrows). Biopsy proved invasive lobular carcinoma (grade 2, stage pT3N1, <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive, <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive, <abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr> negative).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig3f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig3g.jpeg" height="640" width="716" aria-labelledby="fig3g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3g</span>. Tomosynthesis used to improve localization and guide targeted US of two areas of architectural distortion, one at a posterior depth and one located more anteriorly. <b>(a–c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows an anterior distortion (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) that is depicted more clearly on an <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(b)</b>. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(c)</b> shows a subtle posterior-depth distortion and mass (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>), findings seen at tomosynthesis only; the <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> image in <b>a</b> shows only a posterior asymmetry. Insets show zoomed-in area of interest. <b>(d, e)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis images show use of the localization bar. Because correlates for the two architectural distortions were not readily identified on a craniocaudal view, the tomosynthesis localization bar on <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> images was used to better pinpoint positions in the medial-to-lateral plane on the craniocaudal view. According to the localization bar, the anterior finding (arrows in <b>d</b>) is shown to be in the lateral breast, and the posterior finding (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) is shown to be in the medial breast. Tomosynthesis localization also guided US evaluation. <b>(f)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the anterior finding (which was seen mammographically in the upper outer quadrant) at the 2-o’clock position. <b>(g)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the posterior finding (seen mammographically in the upper inner quadrant) at the 11-o’clock position. <b>(h, i)</b> Craniocaudal <b>(h)</b> and mediolateral <b>(i)</b> postbiopsy <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images show the biopsy clips at 2 o’clock and 11 o’clock (arrows). Biopsy proved invasive lobular carcinoma (grade 2, stage pT3N1, <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive, <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive, <abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr> negative).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig3g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3h" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig3h.jpeg" height="1117" width="582" aria-labelledby="fig3h" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3h</span>. Tomosynthesis used to improve localization and guide targeted US of two areas of architectural distortion, one at a posterior depth and one located more anteriorly. <b>(a–c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows an anterior distortion (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) that is depicted more clearly on an <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(b)</b>. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(c)</b> shows a subtle posterior-depth distortion and mass (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>), findings seen at tomosynthesis only; the <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> image in <b>a</b> shows only a posterior asymmetry. Insets show zoomed-in area of interest. <b>(d, e)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis images show use of the localization bar. Because correlates for the two architectural distortions were not readily identified on a craniocaudal view, the tomosynthesis localization bar on <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> images was used to better pinpoint positions in the medial-to-lateral plane on the craniocaudal view. According to the localization bar, the anterior finding (arrows in <b>d</b>) is shown to be in the lateral breast, and the posterior finding (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) is shown to be in the medial breast. Tomosynthesis localization also guided US evaluation. <b>(f)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the anterior finding (which was seen mammographically in the upper outer quadrant) at the 2-o’clock position. <b>(g)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the posterior finding (seen mammographically in the upper inner quadrant) at the 11-o’clock position. <b>(h, i)</b> Craniocaudal <b>(h)</b> and mediolateral <b>(i)</b> postbiopsy <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images show the biopsy clips at 2 o’clock and 11 o’clock (arrows). Biopsy proved invasive lobular carcinoma (grade 2, stage pT3N1, <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive, <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive, <abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr> negative).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig3h">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3i" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig3i.jpeg" height="1117" width="550" aria-labelledby="fig3i" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3i</span>. Tomosynthesis used to improve localization and guide targeted US of two areas of architectural distortion, one at a posterior depth and one located more anteriorly. <b>(a–c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows an anterior distortion (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) that is depicted more clearly on an <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(b)</b>. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image <b>(c)</b> shows a subtle posterior-depth distortion and mass (arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>), findings seen at tomosynthesis only; the <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> image in <b>a</b> shows only a posterior asymmetry. Insets show zoomed-in area of interest. <b>(d, e)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis images show use of the localization bar. Because correlates for the two architectural distortions were not readily identified on a craniocaudal view, the tomosynthesis localization bar on <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> images was used to better pinpoint positions in the medial-to-lateral plane on the craniocaudal view. According to the localization bar, the anterior finding (arrows in <b>d</b>) is shown to be in the lateral breast, and the posterior finding (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) is shown to be in the medial breast. Tomosynthesis localization also guided US evaluation. <b>(f)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the anterior finding (which was seen mammographically in the upper outer quadrant) at the 2-o’clock position. <b>(g)</b> US image shows the sonographic correlate of the posterior finding (seen mammographically in the upper inner quadrant) at the 11-o’clock position. <b>(h, i)</b> Craniocaudal <b>(h)</b> and mediolateral <b>(i)</b> postbiopsy <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images show the biopsy clips at 2 o’clock and 11 o’clock (arrows). Biopsy proved invasive lobular carcinoma (grade 2, stage pT3N1, <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive, <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive, <abbr title="human epidermal growth factor receptor 2">HER2</abbr> negative).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig3i">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig4a.jpeg" height="689" width="782" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Use of landmarks seen only at tomosynthesis to guide identification of architectural distortion at US. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal tomosynthesis image shows a small cyst (circled) adjacent to a subtle architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On a US image, the cyst (arrowhead) was used as a landmark to search for the correlate of the architectural distortion (arrow). US-guided core needle biopsy of the mass demonstrated invasive ductal carcinoma, grade 1, stage pT1aN0.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig4b.jpeg" height="689" width="893" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Use of landmarks seen only at tomosynthesis to guide identification of architectural distortion at US. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal tomosynthesis image shows a small cyst (circled) adjacent to a subtle architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On a US image, the cyst (arrowhead) was used as a landmark to search for the correlate of the architectural distortion (arrow). US-guided core needle biopsy of the mass demonstrated invasive ductal carcinoma, grade 1, stage pT1aN0.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig5a.jpeg" height="1072" width="444" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Use of spot compression tomosynthesis to increase the conspicuity of subtle architectural distortion. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> full-field tomosynthesis image depicts a distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> spot compression tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) more clearly shows the finding (arrow), which was proved to be invasive ductal carcinoma with tubulolobular features.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig5b.jpeg" height="1072" width="881" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Use of spot compression tomosynthesis to increase the conspicuity of subtle architectural distortion. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> full-field tomosynthesis image depicts a distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> spot compression tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) more clearly shows the finding (arrow), which was proved to be invasive ductal carcinoma with tubulolobular features.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig6a.jpeg" height="834" width="774" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. In a case of invasive lobular carcinoma, <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> full-field tomosynthesis image <b>(a)</b> shows an architectural distortion (arrow) well enough to obviate the spot compression view <b>(b)</b>. Insets show zoomed-in area of interest.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig6b.jpeg" height="834" width="901" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. In a case of invasive lobular carcinoma, <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> full-field tomosynthesis image <b>(a)</b> shows an architectural distortion (arrow) well enough to obviate the spot compression view <b>(b)</b>. Insets show zoomed-in area of interest.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig7a.jpeg" height="862" width="869" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Landmarks at <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> imaging used to guide conventional stereotactic biopsy of tomosynthesis-visible architectural distortion with no US or MR imaging correlate. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows a subtle architectural distortion. <b>(b)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) does not show the distortion as clearly. Both the tomosynthesis and <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images, however, show a cyst posterior to the architectural distortion and an anterior fat–fibrous tissue interface. <b>(c)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> postbiopsy image shows the biopsy marker at the expected location. <b>(d)</b> Low-power photomicrograph of specimen from core biopsy shows ductule and stromal proliferation characteristic of sclerosing adenosis, a benign entity that manifests as architectural distortion. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig7b.jpeg" height="887" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Landmarks at <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> imaging used to guide conventional stereotactic biopsy of tomosynthesis-visible architectural distortion with no US or MR imaging correlate. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows a subtle architectural distortion. <b>(b)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) does not show the distortion as clearly. Both the tomosynthesis and <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images, however, show a cyst posterior to the architectural distortion and an anterior fat–fibrous tissue interface. <b>(c)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> postbiopsy image shows the biopsy marker at the expected location. <b>(d)</b> Low-power photomicrograph of specimen from core biopsy shows ductule and stromal proliferation characteristic of sclerosing adenosis, a benign entity that manifests as architectural distortion. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig7c.jpeg" height="862" width="356" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Landmarks at <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> imaging used to guide conventional stereotactic biopsy of tomosynthesis-visible architectural distortion with no US or MR imaging correlate. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows a subtle architectural distortion. <b>(b)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) does not show the distortion as clearly. Both the tomosynthesis and <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images, however, show a cyst posterior to the architectural distortion and an anterior fat–fibrous tissue interface. <b>(c)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> postbiopsy image shows the biopsy marker at the expected location. <b>(d)</b> Low-power photomicrograph of specimen from core biopsy shows ductule and stromal proliferation characteristic of sclerosing adenosis, a benign entity that manifests as architectural distortion. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig7d.jpeg" height="887" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. Landmarks at <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> imaging used to guide conventional stereotactic biopsy of tomosynthesis-visible architectural distortion with no US or MR imaging correlate. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows a subtle architectural distortion. <b>(b)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) does not show the distortion as clearly. Both the tomosynthesis and <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> images, however, show a cyst posterior to the architectural distortion and an anterior fat–fibrous tissue interface. <b>(c)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> postbiopsy image shows the biopsy marker at the expected location. <b>(d)</b> Low-power photomicrograph of specimen from core biopsy shows ductule and stromal proliferation characteristic of sclerosing adenosis, a benign entity that manifests as architectural distortion. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig8a.jpeg" height="851" width="923" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Tomosynthesis-guided needle localization. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) <b>(a)</b> shows an architectural distortion (arrow) with an imaging correlate seen on an axial contrast-enhanced MR subtraction image <b>(b)</b>. At second-look US (not shown), a possible correlate was seen, and US-guided core needle biopsy demonstrated a complex sclerosing lesion and atypical ductal hyperplasia. <b>(c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image shows that the biopsy clip (arrowhead in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>) is anterior to the architectural distortion (arrow), and thus both the second-look US finding and the biopsy are discordant. MR imaging–guided biopsy was attempted but was terminated because of the patient’s extreme anxiety. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> 2D spot compression image shows the wire in place after tomosynthesis-guided needle localization. Histopathologic analysis showed ductal intraepithelial neoplasia grade 1c (ductal carcinoma in situ, grade 1; 2.5 × 1.8 cm; <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive; <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig8b.jpeg" height="851" width="652" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Tomosynthesis-guided needle localization. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) <b>(a)</b> shows an architectural distortion (arrow) with an imaging correlate seen on an axial contrast-enhanced MR subtraction image <b>(b)</b>. At second-look US (not shown), a possible correlate was seen, and US-guided core needle biopsy demonstrated a complex sclerosing lesion and atypical ductal hyperplasia. <b>(c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image shows that the biopsy clip (arrowhead in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>) is anterior to the architectural distortion (arrow), and thus both the second-look US finding and the biopsy are discordant. MR imaging–guided biopsy was attempted but was terminated because of the patient’s extreme anxiety. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> 2D spot compression image shows the wire in place after tomosynthesis-guided needle localization. Histopathologic analysis showed ductal intraepithelial neoplasia grade 1c (ductal carcinoma in situ, grade 1; 2.5 × 1.8 cm; <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive; <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig8c.jpeg" height="1219" width="652" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Tomosynthesis-guided needle localization. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) <b>(a)</b> shows an architectural distortion (arrow) with an imaging correlate seen on an axial contrast-enhanced MR subtraction image <b>(b)</b>. At second-look US (not shown), a possible correlate was seen, and US-guided core needle biopsy demonstrated a complex sclerosing lesion and atypical ductal hyperplasia. <b>(c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image shows that the biopsy clip (arrowhead in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>) is anterior to the architectural distortion (arrow), and thus both the second-look US finding and the biopsy are discordant. MR imaging–guided biopsy was attempted but was terminated because of the patient’s extreme anxiety. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> 2D spot compression image shows the wire in place after tomosynthesis-guided needle localization. Histopathologic analysis showed ductal intraepithelial neoplasia grade 1c (ductal carcinoma in situ, grade 1; 2.5 × 1.8 cm; <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive; <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig8d.jpeg" height="1219" width="373" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. Tomosynthesis-guided needle localization. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) <b>(a)</b> shows an architectural distortion (arrow) with an imaging correlate seen on an axial contrast-enhanced MR subtraction image <b>(b)</b>. At second-look US (not shown), a possible correlate was seen, and US-guided core needle biopsy demonstrated a complex sclerosing lesion and atypical ductal hyperplasia. <b>(c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> tomosynthesis image shows that the biopsy clip (arrowhead in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>) is anterior to the architectural distortion (arrow), and thus both the second-look US finding and the biopsy are discordant. MR imaging–guided biopsy was attempted but was terminated because of the patient’s extreme anxiety. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> 2D spot compression image shows the wire in place after tomosynthesis-guided needle localization. Histopathologic analysis showed ductal intraepithelial neoplasia grade 1c (ductal carcinoma in situ, grade 1; 2.5 × 1.8 cm; <abbr title="estrogen receptor">ER</abbr> positive; <abbr title="progesterone receptor">PR</abbr> positive).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig9a.jpeg" height="717" width="857" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Use of MR imaging to permit MR imaging–guided biopsy of architectural distortion in the absence of a US correlate. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows an architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> mammographic image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) less clearly shows the architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR subtraction image shows a correlative irregular enhancing mass (arrow). MR imaging–guided biopsy demonstrated invasive tubular carcinoma. An associated radial scar was found at surgical excision. <b>(d, e)</b> Low-power photomicrographs of the lumpectomy specimen show a radial scar with radially arranged ducts <b>(d)</b>, and tubular carcinoma characterized by haphazard distribution of well-formed tubules with open lumina and lacking a myoepithelial layer associated with a fibroblastic stroma <b>(e)</b>. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×1 [<b>d</b>], ×4 [<b>e</b>].)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig9b.jpeg" height="717" width="818" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Use of MR imaging to permit MR imaging–guided biopsy of architectural distortion in the absence of a US correlate. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows an architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> mammographic image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) less clearly shows the architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR subtraction image shows a correlative irregular enhancing mass (arrow). MR imaging–guided biopsy demonstrated invasive tubular carcinoma. An associated radial scar was found at surgical excision. <b>(d, e)</b> Low-power photomicrographs of the lumpectomy specimen show a radial scar with radially arranged ducts <b>(d)</b>, and tubular carcinoma characterized by haphazard distribution of well-formed tubules with open lumina and lacking a myoepithelial layer associated with a fibroblastic stroma <b>(e)</b>. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×1 [<b>d</b>], ×4 [<b>e</b>].)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig9c.jpeg" height="623" width="607" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Use of MR imaging to permit MR imaging–guided biopsy of architectural distortion in the absence of a US correlate. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows an architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> mammographic image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) less clearly shows the architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR subtraction image shows a correlative irregular enhancing mass (arrow). MR imaging–guided biopsy demonstrated invasive tubular carcinoma. An associated radial scar was found at surgical excision. <b>(d, e)</b> Low-power photomicrographs of the lumpectomy specimen show a radial scar with radially arranged ducts <b>(d)</b>, and tubular carcinoma characterized by haphazard distribution of well-formed tubules with open lumina and lacking a myoepithelial layer associated with a fibroblastic stroma <b>(e)</b>. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×1 [<b>d</b>], ×4 [<b>e</b>].)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig9d.jpeg" height="624" width="618" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Use of MR imaging to permit MR imaging–guided biopsy of architectural distortion in the absence of a US correlate. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows an architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> mammographic image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) less clearly shows the architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR subtraction image shows a correlative irregular enhancing mass (arrow). MR imaging–guided biopsy demonstrated invasive tubular carcinoma. An associated radial scar was found at surgical excision. <b>(d, e)</b> Low-power photomicrographs of the lumpectomy specimen show a radial scar with radially arranged ducts <b>(d)</b>, and tubular carcinoma characterized by haphazard distribution of well-formed tubules with open lumina and lacking a myoepithelial layer associated with a fibroblastic stroma <b>(e)</b>. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×1 [<b>d</b>], ×4 [<b>e</b>].)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig9e.jpeg" height="623" width="625" aria-labelledby="fig9e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9e</span>. Use of MR imaging to permit MR imaging–guided biopsy of architectural distortion in the absence of a US correlate. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal tomosynthesis image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) shows an architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Craniocaudal <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> mammographic image with zoomed-in area of interest (inset) less clearly shows the architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR subtraction image shows a correlative irregular enhancing mass (arrow). MR imaging–guided biopsy demonstrated invasive tubular carcinoma. An associated radial scar was found at surgical excision. <b>(d, e)</b> Low-power photomicrographs of the lumpectomy specimen show a radial scar with radially arranged ducts <b>(d)</b>, and tubular carcinoma characterized by haphazard distribution of well-formed tubules with open lumina and lacking a myoepithelial layer associated with a fibroblastic stroma <b>(e)</b>. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×1 [<b>d</b>], ×4 [<b>e</b>].)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig9e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150093/asset/images/large/rg.2016150093.fig10.jpeg" height="1619" width="3399" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Diagram shows the proposed management algorithm for tomosynthesis-detected architectural distortion. <i>AD</i> = architectural distortion, <i>MRI</i> = MR imaging, <i>tomo</i> = tomosynthesis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150093&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1"